=========================================================
PHILOSOPHY 
=========================================================

think of the spice profile in layers: 
    1) base - earthy spices (cumin, coriander, turmeric) 
    2) middle - aromatic spices (cardamom, cinnamon, cloves) 
    3) top - bright spices (pepper, chili, sumac) 

spices should compliment, not dominate. 
    they should enhnace the main ingredient, not mask it. 

=========================================================
WHEN TO USE SPICES 
=========================================================

early in cooking            whole spices for infusing oils and broths (i.e. cumin seeds in hot oil) 
midway                      ground spices for depth and integration 
finish                      delicate spices for aroma and brightness (i.e. saffron, cracked pepper) 

=========================================================
HOW TO BALANCE SPICES 
=========================================================

heat vs sweet               chili + cinnamon or nutmeg 
earthy vs acidic            cumin + lime or sumac 
warm vs cool                cardamom + mint 

as a rule start small. spices intensify as they cook. 

=========================================================
TECHNIQUES FOR MAX FLAVOR 
=========================================================

- toast whole spices in oil to release volatile oils 
- use a spice grinder or mortar for peak aroma 
- layering: add spices at different stages to create complexity 
- infusion: steep spices in cream, stock, or syrup for subtle flavor 


=========================================================
SPICES & HOW TO USE THEM 
=========================================================

Warm & Aromatic
    Cinnamon (sticks, ground)               sweet dishes, braises, middle eastern stews
    Nutmeg                                  cream sauces, custards, baked goods 
    Cloves                                  pickling, spice blends, slow-cooked meats
    Allspice                                warm, sweet-spicy blend; pumpkin pie, jerk seasoning, stews
    Cardamom (green, black)                 curries, chai, scandinavian pastries 

Earthy & Savory
    Cumin (whole seeds, ground)             indian curries, mexican chili, middle eastern pilafs 
    Coriander (seeds, ground)               citrus-like: marinades, soups 
    Turmeric                                color + earthy tone: use sparingly in curries, rice 
    Fenugreek                               bitter-sweet: essential in indian blends 
    Mustard Seeds (yellow, black)           tempering in indian dishes, pickles 

Hot & Pungent
    Black Pepper (whole, cracked, ground)   universal, finish dishes for aroma 
    White Pepper                            mild heat, earth; light-colored dishes i.e. white soups, cream sauce 
    Chili Powder                            usually earthy, smoky; use in mexican food, rubs, soups, stews
    Paprika (sweet, smoked, hot)            adds color & mild sweetness; hungarian, spanish dishes 
    Cayenne Pepper                          controlled heat; soups, sauces 
    Aleppo Pepper                           

Sweet & Floral
    Star Anise                              broths, braises, asian dishes 
    Vanilla (beans, extract)                desserts, sauces 
    Saffron                                 infuse in warm liquid; risotto, paella
    Mace                                    warm, aromatic; use in light sauces / soups where nutmeg is too strong 

